# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carnot-heat-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature is typically expressed using the Kelvin scale, on which the unit of measurement is the *kelvin* (unit symbol: K).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This unit is the same interval as the degree Celsius, used on the Celsius scale but the scales are offset so that 0 K on the Kelvin scale corresponds to absolute zero.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] For comparison, a temperature of 295 K corresponds to 21.85 °C and 71.33 °F.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Another absolute scale of temperature is the Rankine scale, which is based on the Fahrenheit degree interval.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature can be defined in purely thermodynamic terms using the Carnot cycle.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature was rigorously defined historically long before particles such as atoms, molecules, and electrons were fully understood.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The International System of Units (SI) specifies the absolute scale for measuring temperature, and the unit of measure *kelvin* (symbol: K) for specific values along the scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] A temperature interval of one degree Celsius is the same as one kelvin.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Since the 2019 revision of the SI, the kelvin has been defined in relation to the *physical property* underlying thermodynamic temperature: the kinetic energy of atomic free particle motion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The revision fixed the Boltzmann constant at exactly 1.380649×10−23 J⋅K−1.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The property that imbues material substances with a temperature can be readily understood by examining the ideal gas law, which relates, through the Boltzmann constant, how heat energy causes precisely defined changes in the pressure and temperature of certain gases.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because monatomic gases like helium and argon behave kinetically like freely moving perfectly elastic and spherical billiard balls that move only in a specific subset of the possible motions that can occur in matter: that comprising the three *translational* degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The translational degrees of freedom are the familiar billiard ball-like movements along the *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes of 3D space (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why the noble gases all have the same heat capacity per atom and why that value is lowest of all the gases.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Molecules (two or more chemically bound atoms), however, have *internal structure* and therefore have additional *internal* degrees of freedom (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] 3*, below), which has the effect that molecules absorb more heat energy for any given rise in temperature than do the monatomic gases.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Heat energy is born in all available degrees of freedom; this is in accordance with the equipartition theorem, so all available internal degrees of freedom have the same average energy as do their three external degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] However, the property that gives all gases their pressure, which is the net force per unit area on a container arising from gas particles recoiling off it, is a function of the kinetic energy borne in the freely moving atoms' and molecules' three translational degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Fixing the Boltzmann constant at a specific value had the effect of precisely establishing the magnitude of the kelvin in terms of the average kinetic behavior of the noble gases.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Moreover, the *starting point* of the thermodynamic temperature scale, absolute zero, was reaffirmed as the point at which *zero average kinetic energy* remains in a sample; the only remaining particle motion being that comprising random vibrations due to zero-point energy.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The numerical zero of a temperature scale is not bound to the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Nevertheless, some temperature scales have their numerical zero coincident with the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Examples are the Kelvin temperature scale and the Rankine temperature scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Other temperature scales have their numerical zero far from the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Examples are the Celsius scale and the Fahrenheit scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] At the zero point of thermodynamic temperature, absolute zero, the particle constituents of matter have minimal motion and can become no colder.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Absolute zero, which is a temperature of zero kelvins (0 K), precisely corresponds to −273.15 °C and −459.67 °F.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Matter at absolute zero has no remaining transferable average kinetic energy and the only remaining particle motion is due to an ever-pervasive quantum mechanical phenomenon called ZPE (zero-point energy).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Temperature is generally expressed in absolute terms when scientifically examining temperature's interrelationships with certain other physical properties of matter such as its volume or pressure (see Gay-Lussac's law), or the wavelength of its emitted black-body radiation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Absolute temperature is also useful when calculating chemical reaction rates (see Arrhenius equation).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Though there have been many other temperature scales throughout history, there have been only two scales for measuring thermodynamic temperature which have absolute zero as their null point (0): The Kelvin scale and the Rankine scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Throughout the scientific world where modern measurements are nearly always made using the International System of Units, thermodynamic temperature is measured using the Kelvin scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The Rankine scale is part of English engineering units and finds use in certain engineering fields, particularly in legacy reference works.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The Rankine scale uses the *degree Rankine* (symbol: °R) as its unit, which is the same magnitude as the degree Fahrenheit (symbol: °F).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] A unit increment of one kelvin is exactly 1.8 times one degree Rankine; thus, to convert a specific temperature on the Kelvin scale to the Rankine scale, ***x* K = 1.8 *x* °R**, and to convert from a temperature on the Rankine scale to the Kelvin scale, ***x* °R = *x*/1.8 K**.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Consequently, absolute zero is "0" for both scales, but the melting point of water ice (0 °C and 273.15 K) is 491.67 °R.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] To convert temperature *intervals* (a span or difference between two temperatures), the formulas from the preceding paragraph are applicable; for instance, an interval of 5 kelvins is precisely equal to an interval of 9 degrees Rankine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] For 65 years, between 1954 and the 2019 revision of the SI, a temperature interval of one kelvin was defined as ⁠1/273.16⁠ of the temperature difference between the triple point of water and absolute zero.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The net effect of this as well as later resolutions was twofold: 1) they defined absolute zero as precisely 0 K, and 2) they defined that the triple point of special isotopically controlled water called Vienna Standard Mean Ocean Water occurred at precisely 273.16 K and 0.01 °C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] One effect of the aforementioned resolutions was that the melting point of water, while *very* close to 273.15 K and 0 °C, was not a defining value and was subject to refinement with more precise measurements.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This shortcoming was addressed by the International Temperature Scale of 1990, or ITS‑90, which defined 13 additional points, from 13.8033 K, to 1,357.77 K.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] While definitional, ITS‑90 had—and still has—some challenges, partly because eight of its extrapolated values depend upon the melting or freezing points of metal samples, which must remain exceedingly pure lest their melting or freezing points be affected—usually depressed.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The solution required that four physical constants, including the Boltzmann constant, be definitionally fixed.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Assigning the Boltzmann constant a precisely defined value had no practical effect on modern thermometry except for the most exquisitely precise measurements.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Afterwards, by defining the Boltzmann constant as exactly 1.380649×10−23 J/K, the 0.37 ppm uncertainty was transferred to the triple point of water, which became an experimentally determined value of 273.1600±0.0001 K (0.0100±0.0001 °C).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Notwithstanding the 2019 revision, water triple-point cells continue to serve in modern thermometry as exceedingly precise calibration references at 273.16 K and 0.01 °C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Moreover, the triple point of water remains one of the 14 calibration points comprising ITS‑90, which spans from the triple point of hydrogen (13.8033 K) to the freezing point of copper (1,357.77 K), which is a nearly hundredfold range of thermodynamic temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature of any *bulk quantity* of a substance (a statistically significant quantity of particles) is directly proportional to the mean average kinetic energy of a specific kind of particle motion known as *translational motion*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] These simple movements in the three *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes dimensions of space means the particles move in the three spatial *degrees of freedom*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This particular form of kinetic energy is sometimes referred to as *kinetic temperature*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Translational motion is but one form of heat energy and is what gives gases not only their temperature, but also their pressure and the vast majority of their volume.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This relationship between the temperature, pressure, and volume of gases is established by the ideal gas law's formula *pV* = *nRT* and is embodied in the gas laws.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Though the kinetic energy borne exclusively in the three translational degrees of freedom comprise the thermodynamic temperature of a substance, molecules, as can be seen in *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] 3*, can have other degrees of freedom, all of which fall under three categories: bond length, bond angle, and rotational.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] All three additional categories are not necessarily available to all molecules, and even for molecules that *can* experience all three, some can be "frozen out" below a certain temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The relationship of kinetic energy, mass, and velocity is given by the formula *E*k = ⁠1/2⁠*mv*2.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, particles with one unit of mass moving at one unit of velocity have precisely the same kinetic energy, and precisely the same temperature, as those with four times the mass but half the velocity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] At any one instant, the proportion of particles moving at a given speed within this range is determined by probability as described by the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] 2* shows the speed distribution of 5500 K helium atoms.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] However, a certain proportion of atoms at any given instant are moving faster while others are moving relatively slowly; some are momentarily at a virtual standstill (off the *x*-axis to the right).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This graph uses *inverse speed* for its *x*-axis so the shape of the curve can easily be compared to the curves in *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] In both graphs, zero on the *x*-axis represents infinite temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Additionally, the *x*- and *y*-axes on both graphs are scaled proportionally.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Although very specialized laboratory equipment is required to directly detect translational motions, the resultant collisions by atoms or molecules with small particles suspended in a fluid produces Brownian motion that can be seen with an ordinary microscope.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The translational motions of elementary particles are *very* fast and temperatures close to absolute zero are required to directly observe them.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, when scientists at the NIST achieved a record-setting low temperature of 700 nK (billionths of a kelvin) in 1994, they used optical lattice laser equipment to adiabatically cool cesium atoms.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] They then turned off the entrapment lasers and directly measured atom velocities of 7 mm per second in order to calculate their temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Formulas for calculating the velocity and speed of translational motion are given in the following footnote.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] It is neither difficult to imagine atomic motions due to kinetic temperature, nor distinguish between such motions and those due to zero-point energy.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Consider the following hypothetical thought experiment, as illustrated in *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] 2.5* at left, with an atom that is exceedingly close to absolute zero.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Imagine peering through a common optical microscope set to 400 power, which is about the maximum practical magnification for optical microscopes.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Such microscopes generally provide fields of view a bit over 0.4 mm in diameter.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] At the center of the field of view is a single levitated argon atom (argon comprises about 0.93% of air) that is illuminated and glowing against a dark backdrop.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] If this argon atom was at a beyond-record-setting *one-trillionth* of a kelvin above absolute zero, and was moving perpendicular to the field of view towards the right, it would require 13.9 seconds to move from the center of the image to the 200 μm tick mark.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] As the argon atom slowly moved, the positional jitter due to zero-point energy would be much less than the 200 nm (0.0002 mm) resolution of an optical microscope.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Importantly, the atom's translational velocity of 14.43 μm/s constitutes all its retained kinetic energy due to not being precisely at absolute zero.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Were the atom *precisely* at absolute zero, imperceptible jostling due to zero-point energy would cause it to very slightly wander, but the atom would perpetually be located, on average, at the same spot within the field of view.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is analogous to a boat that has had its motor turned off and is now bobbing slightly in relatively calm and windless ocean waters; even though the boat randomly drifts to and fro, it stays in the same spot in the long term and makes no headway through the water.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, an atom that was precisely at absolute zero would not be "motionless", and yet, a statistically significant collection of such atoms would have zero net kinetic energy available to transfer to any other collection of atoms.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because regardless of the kinetic temperature of the second collection of atoms, they too experience the effects of zero-point energy.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Such are the consequences of statistical mechanics and the nature of thermodynamics.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] As mentioned above, there are other ways molecules can jiggle besides the three translational degrees of freedom that imbue substances with their kinetic temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] As can be seen in the animation at right, molecules are complex objects; they are a population of atoms and thermal agitation can strain their internal chemical bonds in three different ways: via rotation, bond length, and bond angle movements; these are all types of *internal degrees of freedom*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This makes molecules distinct from *monatomic* substances (consisting of individual atoms) like the noble gases helium and argon, which have only the three translational degrees of freedom (the *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Kinetic energy is stored in molecules' internal degrees of freedom, which gives them an *internal temperature*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Even though these motions are called "internal", the external portions of molecules still move—rather like the jiggling of a stationary water balloon.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This permits the two-way exchange of kinetic energy between internal motions and translational motions with each molecular collision.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, as internal energy is removed from molecules, both their kinetic temperature (the kinetic energy of translational motion) and their internal temperature simultaneously diminish in equal proportions.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This phenomenon is described by the equipartition theorem, which states that for any bulk quantity of a substance in equilibrium, the kinetic energy of particle motion is evenly distributed among all the active degrees of freedom available to the particles.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The kinetic energy stored internally in molecules causes substances to contain more heat energy at any given temperature and to absorb additional internal energy for a given temperature increase.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because any kinetic energy that is, at a given instant, bound in internal motions, is not contributing to the molecules' translational motions at that same instant.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This extra kinetic energy simply increases the amount of internal energy that substance absorbs for a given temperature rise.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This property is known as a substance's specific heat capacity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Different molecules absorb different amounts of internal energy for each incremental increase in temperature; that is, they have different specific heat capacities.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] High specific heat capacity arises, in part, because certain substances' molecules possess more internal degrees of freedom than others do.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, room-temperature nitrogen, which is a diatomic molecule, has *five* active degrees of freedom: the three comprising translational motion plus two rotational degrees of freedom internally.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Not surprisingly, in accordance with the equipartition theorem, nitrogen has five-thirds the specific heat capacity per mole (a specific number of molecules) as do the monatomic gases.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Another example is gasoline (see table showing its specific heat capacity).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Gasoline can absorb a large amount of heat energy per mole with only a modest temperature change because each molecule comprises an average of 21 atoms and therefore has many internal degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Even larger, more complex molecules can have dozens of internal degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] One particular heat conduction mechanism occurs when translational motion, the particle motion underlying temperature, transfers momentum from particle to particle in collisions.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] In gases, these translational motions are of the nature shown above in *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] As can be seen in that animation, not only does momentum (heat) diffuse throughout the volume of the gas through serial collisions, but entire molecules or atoms can move forward into new territory, bringing their kinetic energy with them.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Consequently, temperature differences equalize throughout gases very quickly—especially for light atoms or molecules; convection speeds this process even more.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Translational motion in *solids*, however, takes the form of *phonons* (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Phonons are constrained, quantized wave packets that travel at the speed of sound of a given substance.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The manner in which phonons interact within a solid determines a variety of its properties, including its thermal conductivity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] In electrically insulating solids, phonon-based heat conduction is *usually* inefficient and such solids are considered *thermal insulators* (such as glass, plastic, rubber, ceramic, and rock).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because in solids, atoms and molecules are locked into place relative to their neighbors and are not free to roam.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Metals however, are not restricted to only phonon-based heat conduction.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermal energy conducts through metals extraordinarily quickly because instead of direct molecule-to-molecule collisions, the vast majority of thermal energy is mediated via very light, mobile *conduction electrons*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why there is a near-perfect correlation between metals' thermal conductivity and their electrical conductivity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Conduction electrons imbue metals with their extraordinary conductivity because they are *delocalized* (i.e., not tied to a specific atom) and behave rather like a sort of quantum gas due to the effects of *zero-point energy* (for more on ZPE, see *Note 1* below).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Furthermore, electrons are relatively light with a rest mass only 1⁄1836 that of a proton.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] However, a bullet accelerates faster than a rifle given an equal force.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Since kinetic energy increases as the square of velocity, nearly all the kinetic energy goes into the bullet, not the rifle, even though both experience the same force from the expanding propellant gases.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] In the same manner, because they are much less massive, thermal energy is readily borne by mobile conduction electrons.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Additionally, because they are delocalized and *very* fast, kinetic thermal energy conducts extremely quickly through metals with abundant conduction electrons.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermal radiation is a byproduct of the collisions arising from various vibrational motions of atoms.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] These collisions cause the electrons of the atoms to emit thermal photons (known as black-body radiation).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Photons are emitted anytime an electric charge is accelerated (as happens when electron clouds of two atoms collide).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Even *individual molecules* with internal temperatures greater than absolute zero also emit black-body radiation from their atoms.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] In any bulk quantity of a substance at equilibrium, black-body photons are emitted across a range of wavelengths in a spectrum that has a bell curve-like shape called a Planck curve (see graph in *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The top of a Planck curve (the peak emittance wavelength) is located in a particular part of the electromagnetic spectrum depending on the temperature of the black-body.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Substances at extreme cryogenic temperatures emit at long radio wavelengths whereas extremely hot temperatures produce short gamma rays (see § Table of thermodynamic temperatures).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Black-body radiation diffuses thermal energy throughout a substance as the photons are absorbed by neighboring atoms, transferring momentum in the process.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Black-body photons also easily escape from a substance and can be absorbed by the ambient environment; kinetic energy is lost in the process.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] As established by the Stefan–Boltzmann law, the intensity of black-body radiation increases as the fourth power of absolute temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus, a black-body at 824 K (just short of glowing dull red) emits 60 times the radiant power as it does at 296 K (room temperature).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why one can so easily feel the radiant heat from hot objects at a distance.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] At higher temperatures, such as those found in an incandescent lamp, black-body radiation can be the principal mechanism by which thermal energy escapes a system.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The table below shows various points on the thermodynamic scale, in order of increasing temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] For a true black body (which the plasma was not).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The Z machine's dominant emission originated from 40 MK electrons (soft x–ray emissions) within the plasma.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The kinetic energy of particle motion is just one contributor to the total thermal energy in a substance; another is *phase transitions*, which are the potential energy of molecular bonds that can form in a substance as it cools (such as during condensing and freezing).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermal energy required for a phase transition is called *latent heat*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This phenomenon may more easily be grasped by considering it in the reverse direction: latent heat is the energy required to *break* chemical bonds (such as during evaporation and melting).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Almost everyone is familiar with the effects of phase transitions; for instance, steam at 100 °C can cause severe burns much faster than the 100 °C air from a hair dryer.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This occurs because a large amount of latent heat is liberated as steam condenses into liquid water on the skin.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Even though thermal energy is liberated or absorbed during phase transitions, pure chemical elements, compounds, and eutectic alloys exhibit no temperature change whatsoever while they undergo them (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Consider one particular type of phase transition: melting.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] When a solid is melting, crystal lattice chemical bonds are being broken apart; the substance is transitioning from what is known as a *more ordered state* to a *less ordered state*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] 7*, the melting of ice is shown within the lower left box heading from blue to green.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] At one specific thermodynamic point, the melting point (which is 0 °C across a wide pressure range in the case of water), all the atoms or molecules are, on average, at the maximum energy threshold their chemical bonds can withstand without breaking away from the lattice.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Chemical bonds are all-or-nothing forces: they either hold fast, or break; there is no in-between state.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The effect is rather like popcorn: at a certain temperature, additional thermal energy cannot make the kernels any hotter until the transition (popping) is complete.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] If the process is reversed (as in the freezing of a liquid), thermal energy must be removed from a substance.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] As stated above, the thermal energy required for a phase transition is called *latent heat*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] In the specific cases of melting and freezing, it is called *enthalpy of fusion* or *heat of fusion*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] If the molecular bonds in a crystal lattice are strong, the heat of fusion can be relatively great, typically in the range of 6 to 30 kJ per mole for water and most of the metallic elements.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] If the substance is one of the monatomic gases (which have little tendency to form molecular bonds) the heat of fusion is more modest, ranging from 0.021 to 2.3 kJ per mole.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Relatively speaking, phase transitions can be truly energetic events.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] To completely melt ice at 0 °C into water at 0 °C, one must add roughly 80 times the thermal energy as is required to increase the temperature of the same mass of liquid water by one degree Celsius.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The metals' ratios are even greater, typically in the range of 400 to 1200 times.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The phase transition of boiling is much more energetic than freezing.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, the energy required to completely boil or vaporize water (what is known as *enthalpy of vaporization*) is roughly 540 times that required for a one-degree increase.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Water's sizable enthalpy of vaporization is why one's skin can be burned so quickly as steam condenses on it (heading from red to green in *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] 7* above); water vapors (gas phase) are liquefied on the skin with releasing a large amount of energy (enthalpy) to the environment including the skin, resulting in skin damage.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Water's highly energetic enthalpy of vaporization is also an important factor underlying why *solar pool covers* (floating, insulated blankets that cover swimming pools when the pools are not in use) are so effective at reducing heating costs: they prevent evaporation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] (In other words, taking energy from water when it is evaporated is limited.) For instance, the evaporation of just 20 mm of water from a 1.29 m-deep pool chills its water 8.4 °C (15.1 °F).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The total energy of all translational and internal particle motions, including that of conduction electrons, plus the potential energy of phase changes, plus zero-point energy of a substance comprise the *internal energy* of it.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] When particles of a substance are as close as possible to complete rest and retain only ZPE (zero-point energy)-induced quantum mechanical motion, the substance is at the temperature of absolute zero (T = 0).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Often, all the phase changes that *can* occur in a substance, *will* have occurred by the time it reaches absolute zero.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Notably, T = 0 helium remains liquid at room pressure (*Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] 9* at right) and must be under a pressure of at least 25 bar (2.5 MPa) to crystallize.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because helium's heat of fusion (the energy required to melt helium ice) is so low (only 21 joules per mole) that the motion-inducing effect of zero-point energy is sufficient to prevent it from freezing at lower pressures.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] A further complication is that many solids change their crystal structure to more compact arrangements at extremely high pressures (up to millions of bars, or hundreds of gigapascals).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] These are known as *solid–solid phase transitions* wherein latent heat is liberated as a crystal lattice changes to a more thermodynamically favorable, compact one.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The above complexities make for rather cumbersome blanket statements regarding the internal energy in T = 0 substances.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Regardless of pressure though, what *can* be said is that at absolute zero, all solids with a lowest-energy crystal lattice such those with a *closest-packed arrangement* (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] 8*, above left) contain minimal internal energy, retaining only that due to the ever-present background of zero-point energy.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] One can also say that for a given substance at constant pressure, absolute zero is the point of lowest *enthalpy* (a measure of work potential that takes internal energy, pressure, and volume into consideration).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Lastly, all T = 0 substances contain zero kinetic thermal energy.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature is useful not only for scientists, it can also be useful for lay-people in many disciplines involving gases.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] By expressing variables in absolute terms and applying Gay-Lussac's law of temperature/pressure proportionality, solutions to everyday problems are straightforward; for instance, calculating how a temperature change affects the pressure inside an automobile tire.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] If the tire has a cold gage pressure of 200 kPa, then its absolute pressure is 300 kPa.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Room temperature ("cold" in tire terms) is 296 K.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] If the tire temperature is 20 °C hotter (20 kelvins), the solution is calculated as ⁠316 K/296 K⁠ = 6.8% greater thermodynamic temperature *and* absolute pressure; that is, an absolute pressure of 320 kPa, which is a gage pressure of 220 kPa.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature is closely linked to the ideal gas law and its consequences.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] It can be linked also to the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature can be shown to have special properties, and in particular can be seen to be uniquely defined (up to some constant multiplicative factor) by considering the efficiency of idealized heat engines.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus the ratio *T*2/*T*1 of two temperatures *T*1 and *T*2 is the same in all absolute scales.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Strictly speaking, the temperature of a system is well-defined only if it is at thermal equilibrium.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] From a microscopic viewpoint, a material is at thermal equilibrium if the quantity of heat between its individual particles cancel out.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] There are many possible scales of temperature, derived from a variety of observations of physical phenomena.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Loosely stated, temperature differences dictate the direction of heat between two systems such that their combined energy is maximally distributed among their lowest possible states.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] To better understand the relationship between temperature and entropy, consider the relationship between heat, work and temperature illustrated in the Carnot heat engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The engine converts heat into work by directing a temperature gradient between a higher temperature heat source, *T*H, and a lower temperature heat sink, *T*C, through a gas filled piston.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The work done per cycle is equal in magnitude to net heat taken up, which is sum of the heat *q*H taken up by the engine from the high-temperature source, plus the waste heat given off by the engine, *q*C < 0.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus the efficiency depends only on |*q*C| / |*q*H|.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Carnot's theorem states that all reversible engines operating between the same heat reservoirs are equally efficient.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] In addition, a reversible heat engine operating between a pair of thermal reservoirs at temperatures *T*1 and *T*3 must have the same efficiency as one consisting of two cycles, one between *T*1 and another (intermediate) temperature *T*2, and the second between *T*2 and *T*3.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Here, the engine 1 is the one cycle engine, and the engines 2 and 3 make the two cycle engine where there is the intermediate reservoir at *T*2.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] We also have used the fact that the heat $q_{2}$ passes through the intermediate thermal reservoir at $T_{2}$ without losing its energy.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] In order to have the consistency in the last equation, the heat $q_{2}$ flown from the engine 2 to the intermediate reservoir must be equal to the heat $q_{2}^{*}$ flown out from the reservoir to the engine 3.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] But since the first function is *not* a function of *T*2, the product of the final two functions *must* result in the removal of *T*2 as a variable.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] I.e. the ratio of heat exchanged is a function of the respective temperatures at which they occur.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] We can choose any monotonic function for our $g(T)$ ; it is a matter of convenience and convention that we choose $g(T)=T$ .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Choosing then *one* fixed reference temperature (i.e. triple point of water), we establish the thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] Note that for *T*C = 0 the efficiency is 100% and that efficiency becomes greater than 100% for *T*C < 0, which is unrealistic.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p01] The function S is the entropy of the system, mentioned previously, and the change of S around any cycle is zero (as is necessary for any state function).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Guillaume Amontons (1663–1705) published two papers in 1702 and 1703 that may be used to credit him as being the first researcher to deduce the existence of a fundamental (thermodynamic) temperature scale featuring an absolute zero.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] He made the discovery while endeavoring to improve upon the air thermometers in use at the time.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] His J-tube thermometers comprised a mercury column that was supported by a fixed mass of air entrapped within the sensing portion of the thermometer.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In thermodynamic terms, his thermometers relied upon the volume / temperature relationship of gas under constant pressure.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] His measurements of the boiling point of water and the melting point of ice showed that regardless of the mass of air trapped inside his thermometers or the weight of mercury the air was supporting, the reduction in air volume at the ice point was always the same ratio.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] This observation led him to posit that a sufficient reduction in temperature would reduce the air volume to zero.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In fact, his calculations projected that absolute zero was equivalent to −240 °C—only 33.15 degrees short of the true value of −273.15 °C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Amonton's discovery of a one-to-one relationship between absolute temperature and absolute pressure was rediscovered a century later and popularized within the scientific community by Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Today, this principle of thermodynamics is commonly known as *Gay-Lussac's law* but is also known as *Amonton's law*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In 1742, Anders Celsius (1701–1744) created a "backwards" version of the modern Celsius temperature scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In Celsius's original scale, zero represented the boiling point of water and 100 represented the melting point of ice.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In his paper *Observations of two persistent degrees on a thermometer*, he recounted his experiments showing that ice's melting point was effectively unaffected by pressure.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] He also determined with remarkable precision how water's boiling point varied as a function of atmospheric pressure.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] He proposed that zero on his temperature scale (water's boiling point) would be calibrated at the mean barometric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Coincident with the death of Anders Celsius in 1744, the botanist Carl Linnaeus (1707–1778) effectively reversed Celsius's scale upon receipt of his first thermometer featuring a scale where zero represented the melting point of ice and 100 represented water's boiling point.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] The custom-made *Linnaeus-thermometer*, for use in his greenhouses, was made by Daniel Ekström, Sweden's leading maker of scientific instruments at the time.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] For the next 204 years, the scientific and thermometry communities worldwide referred to this scale as the *centigrade scale*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Temperatures on the centigrade scale were often reported simply as *degrees* or, when greater specificity was desired, *degrees centigrade*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] The symbol for temperature values on this scale was °C (in several formats over the years).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] The 9th CGPM (General Conference on Weights and Measures and the CIPM (International Committee for Weights and Measures formally adopted *degree Celsius* (symbol: °C) in 1948.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In his book *Pyrometrie* (1777) completed four months before his death, Johann Heinrich Lambert (1728–1777), sometimes incorrectly referred to as Joseph Lambert, proposed an absolute temperature scale based on the pressure/temperature relationship of a fixed volume of gas.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] This is distinct from the volume/temperature relationship of gas under constant pressure that Guillaume Amontons discovered 75 years earlier.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Lambert stated that absolute zero was the point where a simple straight-line extrapolation reached zero gas pressure and was equal to −270 °C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Notwithstanding the work of Guillaume Amontons 85 years earlier, Jacques Alexandre César Charles (1746–1823) is often credited with discovering (circa 1787), but not publishing, that the volume of a gas under constant pressure is proportional to its absolute temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac (1778–1850) published work in 1802 (acknowledging the unpublished lab notes of Jacques Charles fifteen years earlier) describing how the volume of gas under constant pressure changes linearly with its absolute (thermodynamic) temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] This behavior is called Charles's law and is one of the gas laws.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] His are the first known formulas to use the number 273 for the expansion coefficient of gas relative to the melting point of ice (indicating that absolute zero was equivalent to −273 °C).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] William Thomson (1824–1907), also known as Lord Kelvin, wrote in his 1848 paper "On an Absolute Thermometric Scale" of the need for a scale whereby *infinite cold* (absolute zero) was the scale's zero point, and which used the degree Celsius for its unit increment.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Like Gay-Lussac, Thomson calculated that absolute zero was equivalent to −273 °C on the air thermometers of the time.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] This absolute scale is known today as the Kelvin thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Thomson's value of −273 was derived from 0.00366, which was the accepted expansion coefficient of gas per degree Celsius relative to the ice point.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] The inverse of −0.00366 expressed to five significant digits is −273.22 °C which is remarkably close to the true value of −273.15 °C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In the paper he proposed to define temperature using idealized heat engines.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Note that like Carnot, Kelvin worked under the assumption that heat is conserved ("the conversion of heat (or caloric) into mechanical effect is probably impossible"), and if heat Q goes into the heat engine, then heat Q must come out.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Kelvin, realizing after Joule's experiments that heat is not a conserved quantity but is convertible with mechanical work, modified his scale in the 1851 work *An Account of Carnot's Theory of the Motive Power of Heat*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] The above definition fixes the ratios between absolute temperatures, but it does not fix a scale for absolute temperature.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] For the scale, Thomson proposed to use the Celsius degree, that is, ${\frac {1}{100}}$ the interval between the freezing and the boiling point of water.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In 1859 Macquorn Rankine (1820–1872) proposed a thermodynamic temperature scale similar to William Thomson's but which used the degree Fahrenheit for its unit increment, that is, ${\frac {1}{180}}$ the interval between the freezing and the boiling point of water.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] This absolute scale is known today as the Rankine thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Ludwig Boltzmann (1844–1906) made major contributions to thermodynamics between 1877 and 1884 through an understanding of the role that particle kinetics and black body radiation played.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] His name is now attached to several of the formulas used today in thermodynamics.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Gas thermometry experiments carefully calibrated to the melting point of ice and boiling point of water showed in the 1930s that absolute zero was equivalent to −273.15 °C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Resolution 3 of the 9th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) in 1948 fixed the triple point of water at precisely 0.01 °C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] At this time, the triple point still had no formal definition for its equivalent kelvin value, which the resolution declared "will be fixed at a later date".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] The implication is that if the value of absolute zero measured in the 1930s was truly −273.15 °C, then the triple point of water (0.01 °C) was equivalent to 273.16 K.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Additionally, both the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) and the CGPM formally adopted the name *Celsius* for the *degree Celsius* and the *Celsius temperature scale*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] This, in combination with Resolution 3 of the 9th CGPM, had the effect of defining absolute zero as being precisely zero kelvins and −273.15 °C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Resolution 3 of the 13th CGPM in 1967/1968 renamed the unit increment of thermodynamic temperature *kelvin*, symbol K, replacing *degree absolute*, symbol °K.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] Further, feeling it useful to more explicitly define the magnitude of the unit increment, the 13th CGPM also decided in Resolution 4 that "The kelvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature, is the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] In November 2018, the 26th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) changed the definition of the Kelvin by fixing the Boltzmann constant to 1.380649×10−23 when expressed in the unit J/K.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/absolute-temperature-p02] This change (and other changes in the definition of SI units) was made effective on the 144th anniversary of the Metre Convention, 20 May 2019.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The special case of a rotation with an internal axis passing through the body's own center of mass is known as a **spin** (or *autorotation*).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In that case, the surface intersection of the internal *spin axis* can be called a *pole*; for example, Earth's rotation defines the geographical poles.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A rotation around an axis completely external to the moving body is called a **revolution** (or **orbit**), as in a planetary orbit, e.g., Earth's orbit around the Sun.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The ends of the external *axis of revolution* can be called the *orbital poles*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Either type of rotation is involved in a corresponding type of angular velocity (spin angular velocity and orbital angular velocity) and angular momentum (spin angular momentum and orbital angular momentum).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Mathematically, a rotation is a rigid body movement which, unlike a translation, keeps at least one point fixed.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This definition applies to rotations in two dimensions (in a plane), in which exactly one point is kept fixed; and also in three dimensions (in space), in which additional points may be kept fixed (as in rotation around a fixed axis, as infinite line).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] All rigid body movements are rotations, translations, or combinations of the two.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A rotation is simply a progressive radial orientation to a common point.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] That common point lies within the axis of that motion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The axis is perpendicular to the plane of the motion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] If a rotation around a point or axis is followed by a second rotation around the same point/axis, a third rotation results.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The *reverse* (*inverse*) of a rotation is also a rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Thus, the rotations around a point/axis form a group.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] However, a rotation around a point or axis and a rotation around a different point/axis may result in something other than a rotation, e.g. a translation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Rotations around the *x*, *y* and *z* axes are called *principal rotations*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Rotation around any axis can be performed by taking a rotation around the *x* axis, followed by a rotation around the *y* axis, and followed by a rotation around the *z* axis.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] That is to say, any spatial rotation can be decomposed into a combination of principal rotations.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The combination of any sequence of rotations of an object in three dimensions about a fixed point is always equivalent to a rotation about an axis (which may be considered to be a rotation in the rotation plane that is perpendicular to that axis).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Similarly, the rotation rate of an object in three dimensions at any instant is about some axis, although this axis may be changing over time.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In other than three dimensions, it does not make sense to describe a rotation as being around an axis, since more than one axis through the object may be kept fixed; instead, simple rotations are described as being in a plane.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In four or more dimensions, a combination of two or more rotations about a plane is not in general a rotation in a single plane.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] 2-dimensional rotations, unlike the 3-dimensional ones, possess no axis of rotation, only a point about which the rotation occurs.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This is equivalent, for linear transformations, with saying that there is no direction in the plane which is kept unchanged by a 2-dimensional rotation, except, of course, the identity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The question of the existence of such a direction is the question of existence of an eigenvector for the matrix *A* representing the rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Therefore, there is no real eigenvalue whenever $\cos \theta \neq \pm 1$ , meaning that no real vector in the plane is kept unchanged by *A*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Using the principal arc-cosine, this formula gives a rotation angle satisfying $0\leq \alpha \leq 180^{\circ }$ .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The corresponding rotation axis must be defined to point in a direction that limits the rotation angle to not exceed 180 degrees.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Every proper rotation A in 3D space has an axis of rotation, which is defined such that any vector v that is aligned with the rotation axis will not be affected by rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Accordingly, $Av=v$ , and the rotation axis therefore corresponds to an eigenvector of the rotation matrix associated with an eigenvalue of 1.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] As long as the rotation angle $\alpha$ is nonzero (i.e., the rotation is not the identity tensor), there is one and only one such direction.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Because A has only real components, there is at least one real eigenvalue, and the remaining two eigenvalues must be complex conjugates of each other (see Eigenvalues and eigenvectors#Eigenvalues and the characteristic polynomial).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Knowing that 1 is an eigenvalue, it follows that the remaining two eigenvalues are complex conjugates of each other, but this does not imply that they are complex—they could be real with double multiplicity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In the degenerate case of a rotation angle $\alpha =180^{\circ }$ , the remaining two eigenvalues are both equal to −1.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In the degenerate case of a zero rotation angle, the rotation matrix is the identity, and all three eigenvalues are 1 (which is the only case for which the rotation axis is arbitrary).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A spectral analysis is not required to find the rotation axis.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] If n denotes the unit eigenvector aligned with the rotation axis, and if $\alpha$ denotes the rotation angle, then it can be shown that $2\sin(\alpha )n=\{A_{32}-A_{23},A_{13}-A_{31},A_{21}-A_{12}\}$ .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Consequently, the expense of an eigenvalue analysis can be avoided by simply normalizing this vector *if it has a nonzero magnitude.* On the other hand, if this vector has a zero magnitude, it means that $\sin(\alpha )=0$ .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In other words, this vector will be zero if and only if the rotation angle is 0 or 180 degrees, and the rotation axis may be assigned in this case by normalizing any column of $A+I$ that has a nonzero magnitude.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This discussion applies to a proper rotation, and hence $\det A=1$ .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Any improper orthogonal 3x3 matrix B may be written as $B=-A$ , in which A is proper orthogonal.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] That is, any improper orthogonal 3x3 matrix may be decomposed as a proper rotation (from which an axis of rotation can be found as described above) followed by an inversion (multiplication by −1).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] It follows that the rotation axis of A is also the eigenvector of B corresponding to an eigenvalue of −1.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] As much as every tridimensional rotation has a rotation axis, also every tridimensional rotation has a plane, which is perpendicular to the rotation axis, and which is left invariant by the rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The rotation, restricted to this plane, is an ordinary 2D rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The proof proceeds similarly to the above discussion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] First, suppose that all eigenvalues of the 3D rotation matrix *A* are real.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This means that there is an orthogonal basis, made by the corresponding eigenvectors (which are necessarily orthogonal), over which the effect of the rotation matrix is just stretching it.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] If we write *A* in this basis, it is diagonal; but a diagonal orthogonal matrix is made of just +1s and −1s in the diagonal entries.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Therefore, we do not have a proper rotation, but either the identity or the result of a sequence of reflections.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] It follows, then, that a proper rotation has some complex eigenvalue.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Let *v* be the corresponding eigenvector.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] because, since ${\bar {v}}^{\text{T}}{\bar {v}}$ is real, it equals its complex conjugate $v^{\text{T}}v$ , and ${\bar {v}}^{\text{T}}v$ and $v^{\text{T}}{\bar {v}}$ are both representations of the same scalar product between v and ${\bar {v}}$ .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This means $v+{\bar {v}}$ and $i(v-{\bar {v}})$ are orthogonal vectors.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Also, they are both real vectors by construction.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] These vectors span the same subspace as v and ${\bar {v}}$ , which is an invariant subspace under the application of *A*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Therefore, they span an invariant plane.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This plane is orthogonal to the invariant axis, which corresponds to the remaining eigenvector of *A*, with eigenvalue 1, because of the orthogonality of the eigenvectors of *A*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A vector is said to be rotating if it changes its orientation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This effect is generally only accompanied when its rate of change vector has non-zero perpendicular component to the original vector.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Which also gives a relation of rate of change of unit vector by taking ${\vec {A}}$ , to be such a vector: ${d{\hat {A}} \over dt}\cdot {\hat {A}}=0$ showing that ${\textstyle {d{\hat {A}} \over dt}}$ vector is perpendicular to the vector, ${\vec {A}}$ .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] since the first term is parallel to ${\vec {A}}$ and the second perpendicular to it, we can conclude in general that the parallel and perpendicular components of rate of change of a vector independently influence only the magnitude or orientation of the vector respectively.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Hence, a rotating vector always has a non-zero perpendicular component of its rate of change vector against the vector itself.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] As dimensions increase the number of rotation vectors increases.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Along a four dimensional space (a hypervolume), rotations occur along x, y, z, and w axis.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] An object rotated on a w axis intersects through various volumes, where each intersection is equal to a self contained volume at an angle.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This gives way to a new axis of rotation in a 4d hypervolume, where a 3D object can be rotated perpendicular to the z axis.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The speed of rotation is given by the angular frequency (rad/s) or frequency (turns per time), or period (seconds, days, etc.).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The time-rate of change of angular frequency is angular acceleration (rad/s2), caused by torque.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The angular velocity vector (an *axial vector*) also describes the direction of the axis of rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Similarly, the torque is an axial vector.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The physics of the rotation around a fixed axis is mathematically described with the axis–angle representation of rotations.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] According to the right-hand rule, the direction away from the observer is associated with clockwise rotation and the direction towards the observer with counterclockwise rotation, like a screw.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] It is possible for objects to have periodic circular trajectories without changing their orientation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] These types of motion are treated under circular motion instead of rotation, more specifically as a curvilinear translation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Since translation involves displacement of rigid bodies while preserving the orientation of the body, in the case of curvilinear translation, all the points have the same instantaneous velocity whereas relative motion can only be observed in motions involving rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In rotation, the orientation of the object changes and the change in orientation is independent of the observers whose frames of reference have constant relative orientation over time.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] By Euler's theorem, any change in orientation can be described by rotation about an axis through a chosen reference point.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Hence, the distinction between rotation and circular motion can be made by requiring an instantaneous axis for rotation, a line passing through instantaneous center of circle and perpendicular to the plane of motion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In the example depicting curvilinear translation, the center of circles for the motion lie on a straight line but it is parallel to the plane of motion and hence does not resolve to an axis of rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In contrast, a rotating body will always have its instantaneous axis of zero velocity, perpendicular to the plane of motion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] More generally, due to Chasles' theorem, any motion of rigid bodies can be treated as a composition of **rotation** and translation, called general plane motion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A simple example of pure rotation is considered in rotation around a fixed axis.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Euler rotations provide an alternative description of a rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] It is a composition of three rotations defined as the movement obtained by changing one of the Euler angles while leaving the other two constant.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Euler rotations are never expressed in terms of the external frame, or in terms of the co-moving rotated body frame, but in a mixture.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] They constitute a mixed axes of rotation system, where the first angle moves the line of nodes around the external axis *z*, the second rotates around the line of nodes and the third one is an intrinsic rotation around an axis fixed in the body that moves.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] These rotations are called precession, nutation, and *intrinsic rotation*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A system which behaves the same regardless of how it is oriented in space is said to be rotationally invariant.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] According to Noether's theorem, if the action (the integral over time of its Lagrangian) of a physical system is invariant under rotation, then angular momentum is conserved.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In astronomy, rotation is a commonly observed phenomenon; it includes both spin (auto-rotation) and orbital revolution.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The rotation or spin of a black hole is its only astronomical property other than its mass and charge.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The rotation stores enormous amounts of energy, powering relativistic jets of ionized particles extending thousands of parsecs into space and lasting hundreds of millions of years.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The jets are strong enough to alter the evolution of galaxies.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Black holes spin much faster than neutron stars despite their similar origin in supernova, suggesting that the spinning magnetic field of the neutron star transfers rotational energy to ionized gases exiting the nova explosion.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Stars, planets and similar bodies may spin around on their axes.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The rotation rate of planets in the Solar System was first measured by tracking visual features.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Stellar rotation is measured through Doppler shift or by tracking active surface features.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] An example is sunspots, which rotate around the Sun at the same velocity as the outer gases that make up the Sun.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Under some circumstances orbiting bodies may lock their spin rotation to their orbital rotation around a larger body.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This effect is called tidal locking; the Moon is tidal-locked to the Earth.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This rotation induces a centrifugal acceleration in the reference frame of the Earth which slightly counteracts the effect of gravitation the closer one is to the equator.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Earth's gravity combines both mass effects such that an object weighs slightly less at the equator than at the poles.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Another is that over time the Earth is slightly deformed into an oblate spheroid; a similar equatorial bulge develops for other planets.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Another consequence of the rotation of a planet are the phenomena of precession and nutation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Like a gyroscope, the overall effect is a slight "wobble" in the movement of the axis of a planet.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Currently the tilt of the Earth's axis to its orbital plane (obliquity of the ecliptic) is 23.44 degrees, but this angle changes slowly (over thousands of years).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Most planets in the Solar System, including Earth, spin in the same direction as they orbit the Sun.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Venus may be thought of as rotating slowly backward (or being "upside down").
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Uranus rotates nearly on its side relative to its orbit.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Current speculation is that Uranus started off with a typical prograde orientation and was knocked on its side by a large impact early in its history.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The dwarf planet Pluto (formerly considered a planet) is anomalous in several ways, including that it also rotates on its side.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] While *revolution* is often used as a synonym for *rotation*, in many fields, particularly astronomy and related fields, *revolution*, often referred to as *orbital revolution* for clarity, is used when one body moves around another while *rotation* is used to mean the movement around an axis.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Moons revolve around their planets, planets revolve about their stars (such as the Earth around the Sun); and stars slowly revolve about their galaxial centers.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The motion of the components of galaxies is complex, but it usually includes a rotation component.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In flight dynamics, the principal rotations described with Euler angles above are known as *pitch*, *roll* and *yaw*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The term rotation is also used in aviation to refer to the upward pitch (nose moves up) of an aircraft, particularly when starting the climb after takeoff.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Principal rotations have the advantage of modelling a number of physical systems such as gimbals, and joysticks, so are easily visualised, and are a very compact way of storing a rotation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] But they are difficult to use in calculations as even simple operations like combining rotations are expensive to do, and suffer from a form of gimbal lock where the angles cannot be uniquely calculated for certain rotations.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Different roughness on each side of arrow fletching produces spin in arrow-flight.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] This rotation improves the stability of the arrow in flight and the precision of the trajectory.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A Ferris wheel has a horizontal central axis, and parallel axes for each gondola, where the rotation is opposite, by gravity or mechanically.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] As a result, at any time the orientation of the gondola is upright (not rotated), just translated.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] The tip of the translation vector describes a circle.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A carousel provides rotation about a vertical axis.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Many rides provide a combination of rotations about several axes.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In Chair-O-Planes the rotation about the vertical axis is provided mechanically, while the rotation about the horizontal axis is due to the centripetal force.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] In roller coaster inversions the rotation about the horizontal axis is one or more full cycles, where inertia keeps people in their seats.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Rotation of a ball or other object, usually called *spin*, plays a role in many sports, including topspin and backspin in tennis, *English*, *follow* and *draw* in billiards and pool, curve balls in baseball, spin bowling in cricket, flying disc sports, etc.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Table tennis paddles are manufactured with different surface characteristics to allow the player to impart a greater or lesser amount of spin to the ball.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Rotation of a player one or more times around a vertical axis may be called *spin* in figure skating, *twirling* (of the baton or the performer) in baton twirling, or *360*, *540*, *720*, etc. in snowboarding, etc.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Rotation of a player or performer one or more times around a horizontal axis may be called a flip, roll, somersault, *heli*, etc. in gymnastics, waterskiing, or many other sports, or a *one-and-a-half*, *two-and-a-half*, *gainer* (starting facing away from the water), etc. in diving, etc.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] A combination of vertical and horizontal rotation (back flip with 360°) is called a *möbius* in waterskiing freestyle jumping.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] Rotation of a player around a vertical axis, generally between 180 and 360 degrees, may be called a *spin move* and is used as a deceptive or avoidance manoeuvre, or in an attempt to play, pass, or receive a ball or puck, etc., or to afford a player a view of the goal or other players.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/axis-of-rotation] It is often seen in hockey, basketball, football of various codes, tennis, etc.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/beale-number] In mechanical engineering, the **Beale number** is a parameter that characterizes the performance of Stirling engines.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/beale-number] It is often used to estimate the power output of a Stirling engine design.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/beale-number] For engines operating with a high temperature differential, typical values for the Beale number are in the range 0.11−0.15; where a larger number indicates higher performance.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Born in Paris, Clapeyron studied at the École polytechnique, graduating in 1818.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] In 1820 he and Gabriel Lamé went to Saint Petersburg to teach and work at the school of public works there.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] He returned to Paris only after the Revolution of July 1830, supervising the construction of the first railway lines connecting Paris to Versailles and Paris to Saint-Germain.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] The half brothers Stéphane Mony and Eugène Flachat collaborated in this project, which was financed by Adolphe d'Eichthal(fr), Rothschild, Auguste Thurneyssen, Sanson Davillier and the Péreire brothers.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron took his steam engine designs to England in 1836 to find a manufacturer and engaged Sharp, Roberts and Co.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] From 1844 to 1859 Clapeyron was a professor at École des Ponts et Chaussées.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron married Mélanie Bazaine, daughter of Pierre-Dominique Bazaine (mathematician and ingénieur des ponts), and older sister of Pierre-Dominique (Adolphe) Bazaine (railway engineer) and François Achille Bazaine (Marshal of France).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Though Carnot had developed a compelling analysis of a generalised heat engine, he had employed the clumsy and already unfashionable caloric theory.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron, in his memoire, presented Carnot's work in a more accessible and analytic graphical form, showing the Carnot cycle as a closed curve on an indicator diagram, a chart of pressure against volume (named in his honor **Clapeyron's graph**).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron's analysis of Carnot was more broadly disseminated in 1843 when Johann Poggendorff translated it into German.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] These foundations enabled him to make substantive extensions of Clausius' work, including the formula, now known as the Clausius–Clapeyron relation, which characterises the phase transition between two phases of matter.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] He further considered questions of phase transitions in what later became known as Stefan problems.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron also worked on the characterisation of perfect gases, the equilibrium of homogeneous solids, and calculations of the statics of continuous beams, notably the theorem of three moments (**Clapeyron's theorem**).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] A **bushel** (abbreviation: **bsh.** or **bu.**) is an imperial and US customary unit of volume, based upon an earlier measure of dry capacity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The old bushel was used mostly for agricultural products, such as wheat: in modern usage, the volume is nominal, with bushels denoting a mass defined differently for each commodity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The name "bushel" is also used to translate similar units in other measurement systems.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The word "bushel" was originally used for a container, and later as a unit of measurement.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The name comes from the Old French **boissiel** and **buissiel**, meaning "little box".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] It may further derive from Old French **boise**, thus meaning "little butt".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The bushel is an intermediate value between the pound and ton or tun that was introduced to England following the Norman Conquest.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] Norman statutes made the **London bushel** part of the legal measure of English wine, ale, and grains.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The Assize of Bread and Ale credited to Henry III, c.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] 1266, defined this bushel in terms of the wine gallon, while the c.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] 1300 Assize of Weights and Measures usually credited to Edward I or II defined the London bushel in terms of the larger corn gallon.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] In either case, a London bushel was reckoned to contain 64 pounds, 12 ounces, 20 pennyweight, and 32 grains.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] These measures were based on the relatively light tower pound and were rarely used in Scotland, Ireland, or Wales during the Middle Ages.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] When the Tower system was abolished in the 16th century, the bushel was redefined as 56 avoirdupois pounds.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The **imperial bushel** established by the Weights and Measures Act 1824 described the bushel as the volume of 80 avoirdupois pounds of distilled water in air at 62 °F (17 °C) or 8 imperial gallons.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] This is the bushel in some use in the United Kingdom.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] Thus, there is no distinction between liquid and dry measure in the imperial system.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The **Winchester bushel** is the volume of a cylinder 18.5 in (470 mm) in diameter and 8 in (200 mm) high, which gives an irrational number, of approximately 2150.4202 cubic inches.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The modern **American** or **US bushel** is rounded to exactly 2150.42 cubic inches, a difference of less than one part per ten million.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] In English use, a bushel was a round willow basket with fixed dimensions, and its inside measurements were as follows – base diameter 12 inches, top diameter 18 inches, height 12 inches – thus giving a volume of 2120.58 cubic inches.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] A basket filled level to the top was a bushel.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] A basket filled to the top but overfilled to a height where it overflowed was considered to be a bushel and a peck, a generous measure (a similar concept to a baker's dozen).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The 1950 song "A Bushel and a Peck" from *Guys and Dolls* contains the lyric "I love you, a bushel and a peck", meaning "I am overflowing with love for you".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] Sometimes the basket was made 13 inches high, but with a ring of "waling" (a special willow weaving technique) to mark the 12 inches height: these baskets had a volume of 9311.68 cubic inches.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] Bushels are now most often used as units of mass or weight rather than of volume.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The bushels in which grains are bought and sold on commodity markets or at local grain elevators, and for reports of grain production, are all units of weight.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] This is done by assigning a standard weight to each commodity that is to be measured in bushels.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] These bushels depend on the commodities being measured, and on the moisture content of the commodity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] Other specific values are defined (and those definitions may vary within different jurisdictions, including from state to state in the United States) for other grains, oilseeds, fruits, vegetables, coal, hair and many other commodities.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] Government policy in the United States is to phase out units such as the bushel and replace them with metric mass equivalents.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] A Prussian *Scheffel* was equal to 54.96 litres.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The Polish bushel (**korzec**) was used as measure of dry capacity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] It is divided into 4 quarters (**ćwierć**) and in the early 19th century had a value of 128 L (28 imp gal; 34 US gal) in Warsaw and 501.116 L (110.230 imp gal; 132.381 US gal) in Kraków.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The Spanish bushel (**fanega**) was used as a measure of dry capacity.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] It is roughly equal to 55.5 L (12.2 imp gal; 14.7 US gal) in Castille.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/bushel] The Welsh hobbit was equivalent to two and a half bushels when used for volume; when used for measuring weight the hobbit was dependent on the grain being weighed.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] A **Carnot heat engine** is a theoretical heat engine that operates on the Carnot cycle.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The basic model for this engine was developed by French military engineer Nicolas Léonard Sadi Carnot in 1824.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The **Carnot engine** model was graphically expanded by Benoît Paul Émile Clapeyron in 1834 and mathematically explored by Rudolf Clausius in 1857, work that led to the fundamental thermodynamic concept of entropy.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The Carnot engine is the most efficient heat engine which is theoretically possible.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The efficiency depends only upon the absolute temperatures of the hot and cold heat reservoirs between which it operates.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] A heat engine acts by transferring energy from a warm region to a cool region of space and, in the process, converting some of that energy to mechanical work.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The system may be worked upon by an external force, and in the process, it can transfer thermal energy from a cooler system to a warmer one, thereby acting as a refrigerator or heat pump rather than a heat engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Every thermodynamic system exists in a particular state.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] A thermodynamic cycle occurs when a system is taken through a series of different states, and finally returned to its initial state.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] In the process of going through this cycle, the system may perform work on its surroundings, thereby acting as a heat engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The Carnot engine is a theoretical construct, useful for exploring the efficiency limits of other heat engines.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] An actual Carnot engine, however, would be completely impractical to build.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The Carnot engine was publicized in Sadi Carnot's sole work: *Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire* (1824).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] A short book addressed to practical engineers in popular language, it has been described as "remarkably accessible to modern readers"; "very clearly written ... [the] mathematical arguments are consigned to footnotes".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] It is known that Carnot was anxious to be understood by non-specialists.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] "The purpose of *Reflexions* was to bring to public notice the potential of the steam engine for improving the standard of living in France".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The first useful steam engines were developed in Britain and were typically employed for pumping water out of coal mines.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Since an engine could burn the mine's own coal (including waste coal, which had no commercial value) fuel economy was of little concern.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The incentive to have efficient engines arose in parts of the country where fuel was costly, such as Cornwall.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The mines of Cornwall produced useful metals like tin; but not coal.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The fuel to power their pumping engines had to be imported by sea and was expensive; users were keenly aware that "heat cost money".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] They sought the engine that did the best "duty'", measured in millions of pounds of water lifted one foot high per bushel of coal burnt.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] A practical business measure, it was a crude indication of the thermodynamic efficiency of an engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Cornish engineers were famous for the efficiency of their engines and their achievements were studied avidly, not least in France, where coal was expensive too.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Sadi Carnot's book mentioned three of them by name, Richard Trevithick, Arthur Woolf and Jonathan Hornblower.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Such men developed the Cornish engine in which high pressure steam was cut off early when the piston was at the beginning of its stroke, letting the steam's expansion complete the stroke by itself.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Today it might be called *adiabatic expansion*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Their ideas were enthusiastically taken up in France, where additionally, scientists and engineers were interested in the theory of steam and other engines.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] In the adjacent diagram, from Carnot's 1824 work, *Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire*, there are "two bodies *A* and *B*, kept each at a constant temperature, that of *A* being higher than that of *B*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] These two bodies to which we can give, or from which we can remove the heat without causing their temperatures to vary, exercise the functions of two unlimited reservoirs of caloric.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] We will call the first the furnace and the second the refrigerator." Carnot then explains how we can obtain motive power, i.e., "work", by carrying a certain quantity of heat from body *A* to body *B*.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] It also acts as a cooler and hence can also act as a refrigerator.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The previous image shows the original piston-and-cylinder diagram used by Carnot in discussing his ideal engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The figure at right shows a block diagram of a generic heat engine, such as the Carnot engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] In the diagram, the "working body" (system), a term introduced by Clausius in 1850, can be any fluid or vapor body through which heat *Q* can be introduced or transmitted to produce work.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Carnot had postulated that the fluid body could be any substance capable of expansion, such as vapor of water, vapor of alcohol, vapor of mercury, a permanent gas, air, etc.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Although in those early years, engines came in a number of configurations, typically *Q*H was supplied by a boiler, wherein water was boiled over a furnace; *Q*C was typically removed by a stream of cold flowing water in the form of a condenser located on a separate part of the engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The output work, *W*, is transmitted by the movement of the piston as it is used to turn a crank-arm, which in turn was typically used to power a pulley so as to lift water out of flooded salt mines.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Carnot defined work as "weight lifted through a height".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] **Isentropic (reversible adiabatic) expansion of the gas (isentropic work output).** For this step (B to C) the piston and cylinder are assumed to be thermally insulated, thus they neither gain nor lose heat.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The gas continues to expand, doing work on the surroundings, and losing an equivalent amount of internal energy.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The gas expansion causes it to cool to the "cold" temperature, *T*C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] **Reversible isothermal compression of the gas at the "cold" temperature, *T*C (isothermal heat rejection)** (C to D).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] (In magnitude, this is the same amount of entropy absorbed in step 1.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] We can refer to the first law of thermodynamics to explain this behavior: Δ*U*= *W*+*Q* .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] **Isentropic compression of the gas (isentropic work input)** (D to A).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Once again the piston and cylinder are assumed to be thermally insulated and the cold temperature reservoir is removed.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] During this step, the surroundings continue to do work to further compress the gas and both the temperature and pressure rise now that the heat sink has been removed.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] This additional work increases the internal energy of the gas, compressing it and causing the temperature to rise to *T*H.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] At this point the gas is in the same state as at the start of step 1.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] A corollary to Carnot's theorem states that: All reversible engines operating between the same heat reservoirs are equally efficient.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] It is easily shown that the efficiency η is maximum when the entire cyclic process is a reversible process.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] This means the total entropy of system and surroundings (the entropies of the hot furnace, the "working fluid" of the heat engine, and the cold sink) remains constant when the "working fluid" completes one cycle and returns to its original state.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Since the "working fluid" comes back to the same state after one cycle, and entropy of the system is a state function, the change in entropy of the "working fluid" system is 0.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Thus, it implies that the total entropy change of the furnace and sink is zero, for the process to be reversible and the efficiency of the engine to be maximum.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] This derivation is carried out in the next section.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The coefficient of performance (COP) of the heat engine is the reciprocal of its efficiency.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] For a real heat engine, the total thermodynamic process is generally irreversible.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The working fluid is brought back to its initial state after one cycle, and thus the change of entropy of the fluid system is 0, but the sum of the entropy changes in the hot and cold reservoir in this one cyclical process is greater than 0.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The internal energy of the fluid is also a state variable, so its total change in one cycle is 0.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] During heat transfer from the hot reservoir at *T*H to the fluid, the fluid would have a slightly lower temperature than *T*H, and the process for the fluid may not necessarily remain isothermal.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Let Δ*S*H be the total entropy change of the fluid in the process of intake of heat.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] where the temperature of the fluid T is always slightly lesser than *T*H, in this process.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] where, during this process of transfer of heat to the cold reservoir, the temperature of the fluid T is always slightly greater than *T*C.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] We have only considered the magnitude of the entropy change here.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] To derive this step needs two adiabatic processes involved to show an isentropic process property for the ratio of the changing volumes of two isothermal processes are equal.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] where $\eta ={\frac {W}{Q_{\text{H}}}}$ is the efficiency of the real engine, and $\eta _{\text{I}}$ is the efficiency of the Carnot engine working between the same two reservoirs at the temperatures $T_{\text{H}}$ and $T_{\text{C}}$ .
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] For the Carnot engine, the entire process is 'reversible', and Equation (**7**) is an equality.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Hence, the efficiency of the real engine is always less than the ideal Carnot engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The inequality in Equation (**7**) is essentially the statement of the Clausius theorem.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] According to the second theorem, "The efficiency of the Carnot engine is independent of the nature of the working substance".
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] In 1892 Rudolf Diesel patented an internal combustion engine inspired by the Carnot engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Diesel knew a Carnot engine is an ideal that cannot be built, but he thought he had invented a working approximation.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] His principle was unsound, but in his struggle to implement it he developed a practical Diesel engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The conceptual problem was how to achieve isothermal expansion in an internal combustion engine, since burning fuel at the highest temperature of the cycle would only raise the temperature further.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Diesel's patented solution was: having achieved the highest temperature just by compressing the air, to add a small amount of fuel at a controlled rate, such that heating caused by burning the fuel would be counteracted by cooling caused by air expansion as the piston moved.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Hence all the heat from the fuel would be transformed into work during the isothermal expansion, as required by Carnot's theorem.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] For the idea to work a small mass of fuel would have to be burnt in a huge mass of air.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Diesel first proposed a working engine that would compress air to 250 atmospheres at 800 °C (1,450 °F), then cycle to one atmosphere at 20 °C (50 °F).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] However, this was well beyond the technological capabilities of the day, since it implied a compression ratio of 60:1.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Such an engine, if it could have been built, would have had an efficiency of 73%.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Accordingly, Diesel sought to compromise.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] He calculated that, were he to reduce the peak pressure to a less ambitious 90 atmospheres, he would sacrifice only 5% of the thermal efficiency.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Seeking financial support, he published the "Theory and Construction of a Rational Heat Engine to Take the Place of the Steam Engine and All Presently Known Combustion Engines" (1893).
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Endorsed by scientific opinion, including Lord Kelvin, he won the backing of Krupp and Maschinenfabrik Augsburg.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] He clung to the Carnot cycle as a symbol.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] But years of practical work failed to achieve an isothermal combustion engine, nor could have done, since it requires such an enormous quantity of air that it cannot develop enough power to compress it.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Furthermore, controlled fuel injection turned out to be no easy matter.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Even so, the Diesel engine slowly evolved over 25 years to become a practical high-compression air engine, its fuel injected near the end of the compression stroke and ignited by the heat of compression, capable by 1969 of 40% efficiency.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] The Carnot heat engine is, ultimately, a theoretical construct based on an *idealized* thermodynamic system.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] On a practical human-scale level the Carnot cycle has proven a valuable model, as in advancing the development of the diesel engine.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] However, on a macroscopic scale limitations placed by the model's assumptions prove it impractical, and, ultimately, incapable of doing any work.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] As such, per Carnot's theorem, the Carnot engine may be thought as the theoretical limit of macroscopic scale heat engines rather than any practical device that could ever be built.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Such "infinitesimal" requirements as these (and others) cause the Carnot cycle to take an *infinite amount of time*, rendering the production of work impossible.
[src:carnot-heat-engine/carnot-heat-engine] Other practical requirements that make the Carnot cycle impractical to realize include fine control of the gas, and perfect thermal contact with the surroundings (including high and low temperature reservoirs).
